Author: @jordanhodder8481
Comment:
personally I think this does suffer from demon's souls syndrome where in some cases the art direction decisions are inferior to the original. I'd also say that it's worth noting that they didn't, like, reshoot and mocap the cutscenes so the in the original, they were edited and directed in a way that fit the hardware. I don't know if I'm articulating myself well but I honestly found that, e.g. in Tess's conversation with Joel in the capitol building, the facial animations in the original actually made the scene more emotionally compelling than the remake's fancier versions. I feel like they lean on the worry lines in the forehead and the mouth corners and such a little too heavily. I don't know if I'm the only one there though.

Honestly, ND might have simply lost some talent in the facial animation department after TLOU2's crunch etc, wouldn't be surprised.

Also, I liked the cuts to black in the original tbh. Felt cinematic, whereas the smooth transitions feel a little too of a piece with current trends (i.e. God of War). It works in Part II but that's a game with a very different feel.

Author: @Etalikor
Comment: In October 2024 I finished it for the first time and I enjoyed it. I played it on PC. The story of the game is great. I liked how Joel and Ellie didn't get along very well in the beginning, but over time they started to get used to each other until they became friends. The atmosphere of the game was good. I liked how the environment changes in the game, sometimes you are in the city, then in the nature, I also liked that the seasons change. Graphically, the game looks nice. I liked the sounds and music. Infected were interesting. There are a total of four types of infected. It's interesting how the infected changes. The first type of runner resembles a human. The first type Runner resembles a human, while the fourth type  Bloater does not resemble a human, but rather a golem. I also liked the weapons and that could be upgraded later. As someone who likes to explore environments in games, I found a lot of things, thanks to which I could create something, for example, a health kit, then, for example, use pills to increase my health etc. There is so much I could write about this game. This game is amazing, one of my favorite games, it is all, have a nice day.

Author: @Pseudo_Placebo
Comment:
It's completely incomprehensible how you can, or could, celebrate this game like this. But I assume that console players also have certain expectations... Back then (at release) as well as today. I've actually spent almost 10 hours playing the game on the PC and have thought several times about abandoning it prematurely, which I've now done.
The game is completely undemanding in terms of gameplay, stupid dialog, predictable actions, rarely stupid AI opponents, tedious occupational therapy (push the crate from A to B, take the ladder again and again and place it) and lengthy film sequences, which caused me to release an enormous amount of melatonin. 
I had already agonized over uncharted and hoped that at least with last of usvalles things would change for the better. Ok, fortunately I didn't pay a penny for either, but I wasted my life. Really rarely been so disappointed and with all due love, these titles could have actually stayed console exclusive. I fell for the supposed hype... Well, lesson learned

Ellie: Agh, fuck that‚Äî [She gets up, turning away from Joel.]

Joel: Well, I'm sorry. I trust him better than I trust myself! Is that what you wanna hear?

Ellie: [Turning to face him.] Stop with the bullshit! What are you so afraid of? That I'm gonna end up like Sam? I can't get infected. I can take care of myself.

Joel: How many close calls have we had?

Ellie: Well, we seem to be doing alright so far.

Joel: [Shouts.] And now you'll be doing even better with Tommy! [Turns away.]

Author: @Ralphoifyful
Comment:
Thanks for this much needed confirmation that TLOU II is the perfect story to cater to what Kaczinsky would call "the spiritual leftist". Although the first 20 minutes you dragged the video through a tirade of descriptive praise for the themes of the game (which boil down to a gigantic non-explanation consisting of "I like the themes because they are there"), finally in the "Reflections" part I get to see what I was already suspicious of what your actual ideas on it were gonna be.
People with 10x more talent and intelligence than you have already described in (technical and beyond-technical) detail how the story of TLOU II is an unabashed disaster in narrative, pacing, coherence and characterization. But that's not the real issue, I already knew that (because unlike 99% of TLOU II unconditional fans, I've been reading classical literature for well over 10 years and continue to do so). The issue is that TLOU II is exactly that for you kind: *_opium_*. A caricaturesque excuse of an actual heroic story delivered to tell you that you're not alone in the face of a human world and reality that you don't understand, that you're afraid of, that you resent and that you feel incapable to face with your own capabilities ("there's nothing as terrifying as becoming an adult in the 21st century", your words). 
That's exactly the spiritual background and unconscious prey instinct that exudes your only own original and truly personal point in this entire mess of an "essay". And it's probably the same for Druckmann himself, who is a weak liberal man who couldn't wait to completely subvert the figure and ideal of what Joel represents, after his main idea for the plot of TLOU I was hilariously thrown to the garbage can by Straley. That's why Joel represents something that will truly never coincide with what you point out to here. Which can be summarized in...:
Neither you nor the "new generation" of people who sadly thinks like you are going to change f - ck all. The reality of violence, heroism, manliness, real love for the kin against aliens and against the ideal of abstract humanism... all of those natural human realities will hit you in the face time, and time, and time again. Strong men will always choose force and protection of the own against sheep-instincts of "humanism": that's the fact people like you or Druckmann will never come to term with on a spiritual level, because on all levels concerning the spirit and beyond, you are not strong men. Joel was, he made the unapologetic hero's decision. THAT is THE REAL REASON why he's been the make it or break it for both halves of the TLOU fan community.

Author: @shugaroony
Comment:
I agree with most of what you say, especially as you close your piece about the failures of Joel's generation, and its up to Ellie and Abby's generation to build a better world; but I don't agree about Joel being selfless at all. He acts selfishly - understandably - at the end of the first game, damns mankind (and I also disagree about the world still being fucked up if a cure is found, as for every David or Isaac, there is a Jackson where hope that society can be rebuilt, isn't diminished) and millions of other kids like Ellie, to become clickers or worse. He then tries to manage Ellie's life as much as he can. Some may say thats what a good father does, but its not, he's not allowing her to find herself, and by lying to her about the hospital, only drives a wedge between them, especially as he keeps repeating it. What Ellie and Abby go through, is due to Joel's selfish actions, and his failure to be a positive influence on others around him, even 4 years later when they are settled in Jackson. 

Thankfully, in the end Abby does this, by finding the empathy and compassion is still within her and to try to be a better person, and ironically becomes a kind of Joel for Lev. Ellie's journey is a lot more complex due to the fact she is at almost rock bottom by the game's end, but knows that by destroying the killer of her father, won't bring any solace; however, by sparing Abby, she saves herself - Joel doesn't do this, she has to realise this on her own, even at her absolute lowest. The next part of her journey we hope, will be that redemption, to bring her back into the light.

Author: @bensonabernathy4664
Comment:
I love the title of this video. Because it is seeing that very thing in Abby, that made me like her as a character. When Abby shot Jesse I was super upset, and I wanted to go after Abby and beat her up. I felt that anger. But then seeing Abby's side of the story, especially seeing her go out of her way to help Yara and Lev made me respect and come to root for Abby's survival. 
After Lev's sister was murdered by the WLF, Lev said to Abby that her people killed his sister Yara. Abby's response to that, "Hey, you're my people!" Abby won me over. I teared up hearing that. Because I felt that.
I mean Lev lost everything at this point. His mom, his sister, and the very group he was apart of has turned against him, plus it felt like everything was out to get Lev being the infected, Seraphites, and the WLF.
But in that moment Abby was basically telling Lev that she will be there for him. She will be there to help, support, and protect him. Because Lev was like family.
It's crazy how she became protective of Lev and even Yara and wanting to help them despite only knowing them for what like 3 days.
It was her empathy and humanity that made her this way. Granted part of the motivation was also gratitude that they helped her survive at the hands of the Serephites, and also her trauma of losing her dad. But ultimately I think Abby's actions showed her capability for empathy and humanity.

This was my interpretation, and I could be wrong.

Author: @DeborahChangMD
Comment: While I can appreciate the attempt at an adaptation of one of my favorite stories ever, I find myself really not enjoying the show. Some of the changes made just seemed to lessen the atmosphere, and distract from what little time we had with the characters we‚Äôre supposed to love, considering it was a rather short tv show as is. It was a good attempt, and there is quality to be found in a lot of parts of the show. But the main attraction to this story, being the dynamic between Joel and Ellie, was utterly squandered in the show. A lot of wasted time on things we never asked for, and that really didn‚Äôt add much, if anything at all to the story itself. In fact, what was added, and a good portion of time was spent on, I would argue often detracted from the main story. It was more so just time spent on multiple plotlines that sort of led into the large plot points of the story that we wanted to see, the emotional impact of which had little time left to really be reflected effectively. The show just seemed to lack development for the two characters who needed it the most. I can‚Äôt wrap my head around why they would introduce so many new plotlines while having so much less time to deliver them than even the game had, while it was only telling one. It just led to most of these story beats feeling half baked, making them feel rather inconsequential, while actively sapping valuable time away from the story we wanted to see. And this lack of development ultimately led to the most pivotal points in the story, feeling far less impactful than they really should‚Äôve. Idk. It‚Äôs probably the best video game adaptation we‚Äôve got just looking at it objectively, technically, visually. But I really just don‚Äôt like it very much, which really is too bad. I didn‚Äôt enjoy the story of part 2 much at all, and seeing the direction that the show strayed in, I am really beginning to doubt Neil Druckmanns sole approach to creative writing.

Author: @darkpaster8559
Comment: The last of us 1 was a game that brought us the experience of how it would be to live in the despair and the depravity, of the apocalypse. It shows two survivors taking upon a journey through the whole country, a country now infested with morbid horrific infected, traveling from state to state, risking your life, and surviving close encounters for what? To smuggle a cure in hopes it would succeed? Even if it‚Äôs like a low percentage of it actually working? I feel like the game itself gives us the meaning of selfishness and desperation of what would be like to survive in this apocalyptic world. The weight that Joel and Ellie carried throughout the game knowing that the world and not just the fireflies is dependent on them. In the last part of the game, I like how it ended, because the fireflies themselves didn‚Äôt even give him back his guns, or even let him talk with Ellie to say goodbye, and they even just straight up tried to kill Ellie  without her consent to proceed with procedure. In my book, Joel did the right thing by saving Ellie from being killed, they didn‚Äôt give her a chance to make her decision, but Joel saved her enough for her to make that choice, even if the fireflies had their reasons for doing what they needed to do, it‚Äôs not justified and it shows how they‚Äôre much worser then Joel himself. What Joel did was also immoral and selfish, but that‚Äôs what makes him the best character, he‚Äôs human and I would‚Äôve done the same. I really wished that the 2nd game was more focused on his redemption instead of that mediocre bs storyline of revenge.

Author: @Road_to_Dawn
Comment:
I just realized, that scene at the end of the winter segment is where both Joel and Ellie changed.

That is where Ellie closed herself off, and even to the end of Part 2, (aside from Joel taking her to the museum for her birthday and some of the time she spent with Dina) we almost never really see her open back up again. Not that cheery, eager girl she used to be. On that note, the way she kills David is actually reminiscent of the way she kills Nora in Part 2.

Joel, on the other hand but in a very similar way, changes into a guy who just wants to spend time with his family and enjoy this chance he‚Äôs been given to live again. And (aside from when he kills everyone in the hospital to get Ellie back, which he selfishly does specifically to keep this newfound joy), this is who he is all the way into Part 2.  A changed man, more trusting, more open, and more caring.

Author: @withgreatpower6169
Comment: The only thing I disagree with is some of your veribiage on the gameplay. The gameplay is brilliant in TLOU for several reasons. Everything you do, be it shooting a shotgun, throwing  a bottle, choking a hunter, or walking through a decrepit hotel, feels tangible.  I feel a sense of humanity sinking lower and lower with every life I'm forced to take in the game. Hitting someone with a brick feels satisfying and cruel instead of just something i have to do if i want to progress through the game. Creating that sense of weight and urgency in a game is not easy. Never do I feel like I'm just running through people or infected like fodder. It's heartpounding, it's anxiety inducing, it's truly an immersive experience. Something that also really stands out to me is how I feel playing the game even when I'm not taking immediate action. Just walking throughout that hotel or through Bill's neighborhood is engaging because of how brilliantly crafted the environments and details are. I could also get into the sound design and the role that plays. Its always fun to shoot or hack at things but when I'm at the edge of my seat just taking in the quiet moments like walking through a house or a garage, that all goes back to the gameplay creating that experience.

Author: @franciscomedipro8580
Comment:
In The Last of Us Part II, the creators decided to make Ellie a lesbian, which holds significant value for LGBTQ+ visibility. However, by focusing on her sexual orientation, they missed the opportunity to develop her personality more deeply. This can give the false impression that a tough and strong woman has to be lesbian to be believable, when in reality, a strong character doesn‚Äôt need to be defined by their sexuality.

The problem with this approach is that by putting her sexual orientation at the center of the story, it limits the complexity of the character and reinforces certain stereotypes. Ellie‚Äôs sexuality becomes what defines her, when what should really be important are her strength, her conflicts, and her human relationships.

This approach can make some people think that being tough and strong is automatically tied to being lesbian, when in reality, women can be equally powerful and complex without their sexual orientation determining it. If, instead of focusing on sexuality, the story had explored her character and challenges more deeply, the character could have developed in a much richer and more universal way.
